content.description:
Oh yeah, the good stuff.

Start on Shrimps, then traverse right, reversing the Baggins Left Exit. Once at the back of the cave on jugs, continue through the WORMHOLE! in the roof. It's a tight squeeze to finish!
content.location: Baggins cave. Starts sitting on a huge jug on the slab, finishing in the cave by crawling through a small hole in the roof.

content.description:
A badger...think of the badger. Make your dreams wet and cinch your stomach down (clutch).

The frosting is just the tip of the cake on this one. Put your body through two holes. Don't even think about touching the first one...but the second one? Let it caress your sweet, smooth bod and rip holes in your brand new Brandy Melville brand t-shirt. As you exit the hole, simply walk over to the other hole and go for another lap...or 2, or 3 or 4 or 5 or many.

This is about as good as it gets. And this is just the part of the iceberg that's above the water, there's a lot more iceberg where that came from!!!
content.protection: pads and 4 rings and a necklace
content.location: Start on top of the Baggins cave. Downclimb the Baggins Early Exit without dabbing, then traverse right through good slopers and finish on the one and only Wormhole.

content.description: Start with both hands in the crack feature. There seems to be a left hand sloper, and a left hand finger lock. Go with what you like best. Right hand is on a flat edge. Foot on the little chicken head. Up to the obvious chicken head, and edges to either side. Crux is the top out.
content.location: This is on the west (climbers left) face of Dans boulder where double dyno resides.

content.description: This problem follows a cool sloping rail with surprisingly slick texture up and left to reach the lip of the boulder where jugs are found.  Follow the jugs up and right along the lip until you can mantel.  The height, steep angle, and lack of footholds below the rail all add to the experience.
content.location: Tom's Problem is only about 50 feet from the main roadside boulder, but well hidden by trees and an outcropping of rock.  Approach by taking a trail leading northwest from the Dean Problem (the shot-holed west side of the main roadside boulder).  Tom's Problem is east facing.

content.description:
On the Brake boulder. I started with my right hand on the undercling and my left hand on a nice crimp a little to the left and up. Find a small piece of granite to stick your right toe on and then lift your left foot up to a rather nice edge. Finish it up and then just walk down the back. I thought it was a fun short problem.

There's also a traverse problem starting at the jugs on the low left that goes along the arete to top out at the point.
content.location: Small boulder just a few feet into the trees from the road.  It is just southeast from the large  boulder.

content.description: Sit start on sharp crimps to the right of Tiger Snake, traverse left on slopers and join Tiger Snake
content.location: 10 feet right of Tiger Snake

content.description: Start with right sidepull at head height and left lower undercling. Make a log awkward reach to a jug, grab the arete and reach for the top. Landing is not great.
content.location: 30 or so yards before the cabbage patch, about 10 yards uphill from road.

content.description: It's on the same face as Fat Albert. Start left hand on arete, Right hand side pull crimp. Find some feet and have fun.
Start on jugs, move into the jug crimp on the V10 Baggins variation and top out the same. The throw to the top is a little sketchy since swinging off could result in a gnarly tumble down the slab
content.protection: Pad or two, definitely a good spotter
content.location: Start sitting on the slab rock on a large jug flake to the left of the Baggins cave

content.description: Small edges.
content.location: On the back side of the main Cabbage Patch boulder

content.description: From the Black Bible, description is vague, I found what felt like a V4 start using right hand in a crimp crack about 6ft up, and left hand in a small opening a little further up the crack. Climb the face using the interesting greenish dike feature to the top. Pretty gritty in parts.
content.location: On the West face of a boulder that is on the north side of the east / west trail above Tom’s and Baggins.

content.description: Two move crimp problem
content.location: above baggins

content.description: Climb the diagonaling crack/seam to its end and punch straight up the east face of the prominent monolith below The Egg.
content.protection: Medium/small TCUs and a hand-sized piece. Small wires.
content.location: Follow the trail past Tom's arete to the huge boulder jutting out of the hill. Walk off.

content.description: From BB: Start sitting on crimpers on the right side of the small corridor. Head up to a left slanting rail, then straight up to flat jug. Head up and right to a hidden mono, then mantle.
content.location: North face of Jack's Boulder, next to A Bit Slopey

content.description:
Start sitting in the cave opposite baggins and head up and then right

see

vimeo.com/165603313
content.location: Start in cave opposite baggings

content.description: Climb the south face without using the arete.  Classic.
Start as for Tiger Snake Venom but head up and slightly left avoiding the good holds from the v3 to the right.
content.location: Same start as  Tiger Snake Venom

content.description:
Fun route to get on after warming up on the other problems in the area.

Climb up the arete to the right of Fat Albert, topping out with some technical sloper work.

The first few moves seem just a tad bit harder for shorter folk, as the starting foot will probably be too far down to reach the sidepull.
content.protection: a pad or two is plenty. Flat landing
content.location:
Just to the right of Fat Albert.

Start left hand on a crimpy pinch, and right hand around arete on small crimp.

Top out using slopers to the right of where you started(don't finish on the same face as Fat Albert Gang)

Downclimb using the trees leaning against the boulder

content.description:
Undocumented problem that turned out to have some really interesting holds and movement.

Start on a good sloper and a rounded crimp near the middle of the cave, then traverse left under the roof up the crack, and exit left - video in comments.

Crux for me was getting up out of the crack. Watch out for sharp holds in the crack!
content.location: In a corridor between two boulders just N of the pipeline trail, maybe 20-30 yds NE of Baggins or 30-40 yds NW of double Dyno.

content.description: This beautiful line (thanks to quarrying) is a great lesson in pure arete liebacking.  Core tension down low is the key, especially moving past the crux.  Fun topout.  A sit start adds a move, but the grade's the same.
content.location: Right off the road, same boulder as Dean Problem

content.description: Long reach from  a decent crimpy left hand at chest height to a distant RH crimp.
content.location: The face between Fat Albert Gang and Fungus (arete is off of course)

content.description:
a.k.a.  Dan's Problem

A great problem that will leave you wanting more, or screaming because you left your skin on top.  Start low matching on obvious horn, move left up to next obvious jug.  Commit and make the long throw up to the huge sloping shelf.  Harder if you throw both hands.
content.location: Go up the hill 30ft in between Jack's boulder and Brake Boulder to the Dyno Boulder.  Right in the middle, you can't miss it.

content.description: Arete on southwest corner of the large drilled boulder.  Use the drill holes on the face of the boulder  as single finger holds, along with the drill holes on the arete.  Be prepared for some lie-backs  .
content.location: Shimmy down the tree on the northeast side to get down.

content.description: Pull through three drilled monos and huck for the top. Possibly the best chipped route in the world. Arete is off.
Start on low, huge rail and move straight up.
content.protection: A large pad. Flat and save landing.
content.location: Climb on far right of the double dyno boulder (same start as circus freak, but you go straight up).

content.description: Head up the shallow pockets in the middle of the slab on the small boulder to the left of Dean Problem.  Pretty short but worth a go if you're in the area.
content.location: Center of the face of small boulder to the left of Dean Problem.  Faces the road.

content.description:
The one comes down to fit. If you are

tall

and

are

ok with a mono

, this is super fun and V-easy. If you

are not

tall

and/or

are

not

ok with a mono

, this isn't going to work out for you.
content.location:
Starts on the arete on the L side of the Dean face.

Use a knob just around the arete for the left hand and a side-pull crimp for the right. Aim for the RH mono, get the good feet, go to the top.

https://youtu.be/xHcaUDkbxWE?t=45

content.description:
Obscure one from the old guide, had to clean it up and clear some overgrowth on the top out.

Start sitting on the left end of the crack, do some smeary layback moves up to the arete, then move up over the bulge for an awkward and somewhat exciting top out.
content.protection: 4-5 pads to fully protect it, multilevel landing
content.location: On the SE side of the Cracker Boulder, in between Boone’s Bane and Baggins

content.description:
Start in the horizontal crack just to the right of Double Dyno, and head upward. The guidebook says to climb into the left-angling crack and top out.

It's kind of cool heading up the Michelin Man fat rolls, reaching deep into the adipose tissue to pull yourself up.
content.location: Just to the right of Double Dyno (V2).

content.description:
From BB: Start on crimps and pull hard for the top.

Sit start : V6

I guess if you've hit all the other classics in cabbage patch and are bored, you can do this one...
content.location: Starts just right of Fungus.

content.description:
Super fun technical mantel!

Start on edges below lip of boulder, pull to lip on slopers, then mantel into the scoop using a heel.

I did this with hands on left side, but it's done the other way as well.
content.protection: You'll want a couple of pads and a spotter. Although it's low, there's a brutal rock at the base of the climb, and it's easy to pull a Bane-on-Batman move on that thing.
content.location: About 20 feet uphill from the double dyno. Faces same direction as the double dyno.

content.description:
Sit start on Boone's Bane. Go left around the bulge and up.

First move might be a little scrunchy for the tall folks, but after that it's really fun.
content.location: Boone's Bane boulder

content.description: Start sitting on two low slopers on the left side of the cave. Climb up to the jug, then traverse left ending on "Shrimps"
content.location: Baggins cave, just above Tom's problem

content.description:
SDS on the right side of the cave on a low left hand crimp and a right hand side-pull crimp. Make 2-3 fun moves to the jug then traverse left ending on "Shrimps".

The LCC guide has this at V10 starting on the jug, but according to Mike Beck the original line starts sitting on low crimps. While the low start doesn't change the grade, it adds 2-3 fun moves that are worth doing. So not sure why anyone would decide to cut those moves out.
content.protection: Two pads and a blubber for the sit
content.location: In Baggins cave (above Tom's problem)

content.description: Start on the far right side of the cave, move up and traverse left on slopers to a small crimp, top out between the two boulders (don't dab!)
content.location: From Cabbage Patch, head towards Double Dyno but take the trail heading left instead of going to Double Dyno.  Follow this trail for about 40 feet and look for a trail that heads uphill on the right, leading through a couple bushes to Baggins. Tanner's LCC Climbing app circled the jugs as the start. I started right underneath on two crimps and don't think it changes the grade

content.description: Start on rail under tiered roof. Do some hard moves to the jug and then topout through the crack. V12 if you continue to traverse out left ending on Shrimps.
content.location: up the hill from Tom's Problem

content.description: Start on Rail up and rt of the starting holds for TSV. Make a long -ish reach for a sloper and then use small crimps toclimb the short slab above
content.location: immediately right of Garden Snake

content.description: Start sitting just right of the tree and move straight up to edges, avoiding the problem to the right, mantle straight over the start. V9 Variation finishes on Christopher Reeve. The feet are bad going for the top. The top hold is great if you can get to it.
content.protection: Use two pads, one on the ground, one on the rock to your back. Chance of hitting you head or tail bone when falling is high.
content.location: Cabbage Patch, Jack's Boulder, North Face
